prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We need to reach an rms of 2.4 mJy over 300 km/s that will allow us to detect CII emission down to 3e8 Lsun at z=2, corresponding to SFR of about 20 Msun/yr. We will use all 4 basebands in adjacent configuration, which is allowed in Band9, covering a velocity width of 4000km/s around the average cluster redshift, that is crucial to detect galaxies with different peculiar velocities in the cluster potential, and possibly infalling into it. The use of 4 basebands will also maximize our continuum sensitivity. The lowest spectral resolution will suffice, giving a reasonable data rate for this project. We ask for the coarsest spatial resolution for this detection experiment, most sources should remain basically unresolved.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
We propose to observe [CII] line emission from galaxies in the immediate core of the most distant established, X-ray detected cluster discovered to date, Cl J1449+0856 at z=2. In contrast with both proto-clusters generally found at this epoch and established galaxy clusters seen at lower redshift, the core of Cl J1449+0856 hosts a massive and centrally dominant population of quiescent early-type galaxies, characteristic of an evolved structure, as well as significant star-forming galaxy population.
We expect to detect at least 10 star forming galaxies and reveal additional possibly obscured starbursts down to SFR=20 Msun/yr for a conservative ratio of LCII/LIR =1.5*10^-3, for which we expect comparable S/N>3 detections in both CII and underlying continuum directly probing SFR. We will also search for gas and residual SFR inside 5 spectroscopically confirmed passive ETG cluster members (directly and through stacking). Together with Cycle 1 data covering the CO[3-2] emission and longer wavelength continuum more sensitive to total dust mass, we will obtain an unprecedented view of galaxy formation in the exciting environment of a forming z=2 galaxy cluster.
prp:ObsProposal.prp:scientificCategoryString: Cosmology and the High Redshift Universe
